#### Issue details
When using labels with markdown, xAdvance for GlyphLayout.GlyphRun is not calculated correctly, which results in unwanted spaces in the text.

#### Reproduction steps/code
The easiest way to reproduce this issue is by slightly changing BitmapFontTest.
Add following code to BitmapFontTest.create() method and compare 2 newly added labels.

```
labelToCompareA = new Label("This is a Test Label, to see if color markdown affects labels in any unwanted way!", skin);
labelToCompareB = new Label("This is a [GREEN]Test Label[], to see if color markdown affects labels in any unwanted way!", skin);
		
labelToCompareA.setPosition(100, 350);
labelToCompareB.setPosition(100, 380);
		
labelToCompareA.debug();
labelToCompareB.debug();
		
stage.addActor(labelToCompareA);
stage.addActor(labelToCompareB);
```

#### Screenshot of the issue
![labels](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/16850838/27644664-6a3ae804-5c24-11e7-820b-6fa39f99c9f1.png)



#### Version of LibGDX and/or relevant dependencies
Current master branch is affected by this issue. This problem probably exists for a while though.

#### Please select the affected platforms
I believe all platforms are affected.

#### Issue details
Use UBJsonWriter to write a short[] and then any other kind of data after. Reading back this data with UBJsonReader will result in a "Unrecognized data type, string expected" error though that is not the actual problem and leaves the user without any hint of what has gone wrong. The underlying problem is that the default state ('oldFormat' field set to 'true') of UBJsonReader treats short values as integers and thus over-reads data which leads to the parse() function breaking. This can be seen if only a short[] is written using UBJsonWriter; trying to read it back leads to an EOFException unless 'oldFormat' is set to false. To solve this mismatch between UBJsonWriter and UBJsonReader perhaps there can be a 'useOldFormat' boolean in the UBJsonWriter constructor that, if set to true (defaults to true?), internally converts and writes Shorts as Ints? This would prevent the error and it would alert a user of the two classes of this inter-dependency. This is, of course, only a suggestion without knowing all the background of what went into the code being this way; whatever lets users know what's going on here is the idea. Just trying to save someone else hours of debugging ;) Thanks for your time.

***Update Edit*** - so it turns out that if 'oldFormat = false' then UBJsonReader parse() breaks when trying to read in a .g3db file from FBX-Conv so I guess there is inter-library dependency on this 'oldFormat' field. Below is the new code to see this and attached here is the .g3db file [boneTest.zip](https://github.com/libgdx/libgdx/files/1111827/boneTest.zip) I used (it was generated from a Blender file of a cube and two bones).

#### Reproduction steps/code
```
public class UBJsonReadWriteTest implements ApplicationListener {

	@Override
	public void create () {
		try{
			UBJsonWriter writer = new UBJsonWriter( new FileOutputStream("test.bin") );
			writer.object();
			writer.set("shortArray", new short[]{1,2,3});
                        //comment out following line to see EOFException
			writer.set("stringArray", new String[]{"dog", "hat", "run"});
			writer.pop();
			writer.close();

		}catch(FileNotFoundException fnf){}catch(IOException ioe){}
		UBJsonReader reader = new UBJsonReader();
		//reader.oldFormat = false;
		reader.parse(Gdx.files.getFileHandle("test.bin", Files.FileType.Internal));
	}
	@Override
	public void render () {}
	@Override
	public void dispose () {}
	@Override
	public void resume(){}
	@Override
	public void pause(){}
	@Override
	public void resize(int x, int y){}
}
```
```
public class UBJsonReadWriteTest implements ApplicationListener {
	@Override
	public void create () {
		UBJsonReader ubj = new UBJsonReader();
		ubj.oldFormat = false;
		G3dModelLoader modelLoader = new G3dModelLoader(ubj);
		Model test = modelLoader.loadModel(Gdx.files.getFileHandle("boneTest.g3db", Files.FileType.Internal));
	}
	@Override
	public void render () {}
	@Override
	public void dispose () {}
	@Override
	public void resume(){}
	@Override
	public void pause(){}
	@Override
	public void resize(int x, int y){}
}
```

#### Version of LibGDX and/or relevant dependencies
LibGDX version: 1.9.6
Back-end: LWJGL Desktop Configuration

